english:
  title: Memorial on Celestial Portents
  author: Lim Wan
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your subject has heard it said that offering counsel is not difficult—what is difficult is listening to that counsel. And listening to counsel is not difficult—what is most difficult is acting upon it. Therefore the ancients said: when a loyal minister serves his lord, if his words are cutting and upright, he risks danger before they are heeded; if his words lack cutting truth, they cannot illuminate the Way. In ancient times, during the reign of Emperor Wen of Han, one might say the realm knew no troubles. Yet Jia Yi still found cause for bitter tears and endless sighs.

    Now that heaven's signs grow strange and Your Majesty fears the mandate of Heaven, seeking to hear words of truth and issuing an edict requesting forthright speech—this is truly a blessing for ten thousand generations.

    Your subject has observed in the writings of Dong Zhongshu: "When a state is about to fall into the errors of losing the Way, heaven first sends calamities and prodigies as warnings. If the ruler does not reflect upon himself, heaven sends forth strange omens to frighten and alert him. Should he still not heed, then ruin arrives. This shows that heaven's heart loves its lord and wishes to prevent his downfall. In any age not marked by great disorder, heaven desires only to sustain and preserve. When a ruler responds to heaven's admonition, it must be with sincerity, not merely with empty forms." The transmission says: "Respond to heaven with substance, not with form." By substance we mean virtue; by form we mean such things as today's Daoist rituals and offerings. When a ruler cultivates virtue to respond to heaven, he need not seek blessings—they come of themselves. Should he instead neglect virtue and engage only in empty forms, not only does this bring no benefit; it serves only to offend heaven.

    The Classic says: "Heaven shows no favoritism; it aids only the virtuous." And again: "Millet and grain are not fragrant; only bright virtue is fragrant." Virtue—where else would we seek it? It lies solely in the ruler's intentions and actions. When intentions are good and manifest in deeds, we find examples in Yao, Shun, Yu, Tang, Kings Wen and Wu, and Kings Cheng and Kang. Each act, each measure they undertook aligned with heaven's will, and thus they enjoyed blessings without limit. When intentions are corrupt and manifest in deeds, we find examples in Jie, Zhou, Kings You and Li, and Qin Shi Huang. Each act, each measure they undertook opposed heaven's way—and they could not even preserve their own persons, much less enjoy the realm.

    Moreover, of late celestial signs have multiplied: famines recur, white rainbows pierce the sun, thunder breaks in unexpected ways in the month of正陽—portents unheard of in recent ages. Is it not that Your Majesty responds to heaven with forms but not with substance? Why are the ceremonies so frequent yet the calamities so many? Heaven's warnings are thus, revealing that heaven's heart loves Your Majesty as parents love their child, wishing only to sustain and preserve him. Your Majesty must strive with all sincerity to respond. Reform the present corruptions; reform them by following the legacy of our Progenitor King and reviving the institutions of the Sage King Munjong.

    The Progenitor King's teachings, though I have not heard them in full, surely contained profound wisdom, as confirmed in our histories. The legacy of Sage King Munjong is not distant—I have heard elders speak of it, and found tears flowing unbidden. He practiced frugality himself, promoted the capable and worthy. Ranks and offices were not granted to the undeserving; power was not shifted to favorites. Though relatives might be close, those without merit received no rewards; though loved ones might be near, the guilty were surely punished. Eunuchs and palace attendants were few and carefully chosen—some ten youths for menial tasks, perhaps twenty capable men for service. All officials performed their duties; unnecessary posts were eliminated, affairs simplified, expenditures reduced. The great granaries overflowed, every household had sufficiency, every person had enough. It was called an age of peace. This was our realm's sage and virtuous ruler.

    In recent times, all has been reversed. Officials have multiplied, arrogance and extravagance grow daily, shame and honor are forgotten. Wielding power and trusting in favor, they exploit and extract from the people, adding heavy taxes and forced labor until the common heart is stirred to resentment. If even Jia Yi could witness today's state, would he merely sigh and weep?

    Your subject humbly counsels: to hold yourself accountable, to reflect upon yourself, to respond to heaven's admonition—nothing serves better than to follow the good laws and virtuous governance of your ancestors. Yet implementing ancestral law must displease the powerful. Thus even virtuous measures are reversed by evening if begun in the morning; law lacks constancy. This cannot be Your Majesty's true intention to cultivate virtue. Only if Your Majesty's sincere heart issues from your sacred mind, holding your ministers accountable, appealing to heaven's will, suppressing the deceptions of those near you, cutting off the strange and aberrant teachings, proceeding with daily care—then your great enterprise will increase in splendor, achieving boundless blessings for ten thousand ages.

    These strange teachings of late have arisen greatly through Myojeong. Your subject observes that Myojeong engages only in deception, misleading the ruler—no different from Lin Lingsu of Song. Lingsu wielded heterodox ways to bewitch the former emperor. Ambitious scholars bent themselves in flattery to seek advancement. In those times too, calamities appeared repeatedly, yet the emperor took no heed. When schemes were exhausted and fortune failed, ruin came—and what good was it then to execute Lingsu? Your Majesty has yourself heard of this. Would you tread again the path of the overturned wheel? Because Your Majesty favors Myojeong, the court and all ministers praise him as a sage; his roots have grown deep, his branches fixed—he cannot be uprooted. Since the construction of Taehwa Palace, the people have suffered, bearing the people's resentment. Last year's imperial progress brought disaster to the Buddha's pagoda; this year's progress brought falling stars and horses startled—calamities succeeding one another. This palace, built to seek blessings, has now stood seven or eight years without a single auspicious sign—only repeated calamities. Why is this? Heaven's meaning says: "Evil men delude the ruler. Men may be deceived, but can heaven be deceived?" These recent portents are heaven's warning to Your Majesty. Would Your Majesty spare one treacherous minister and violate heaven's will?

    Your subject entreats: wield your sovereign authority, behead Myojeong. Thus answer heaven's warning above and comfort the people's hearts below. This is the voice of all under heaven, not the private opinion of this foolish minister. Your Majesty, consider it well.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Jia Yi (賈誼) was a celebrated Confucian remonstrant of the Han Dynasty, known for his earnest if tragic attempts to counsel Emperor Wen. He became a symbol of the loyal minister whose wisdom goes unheeded.
  - key: ''
    value: Dong Zhongshu (董仲舒) was a Han Dynasty philosopher who developed an influential theory of resonance between heaven, earth, and human affairs—that celestial portents reflect heavenly judgment on the ruler's virtue.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The reference to Song''s Lin Lingsu (林靈素) and the former emperor invokes a historical cautionary tale: Lingsu was a Daoist charlatan who wielded dangerous influence through heterodox practices, ultimately contributing to political chaos.'
  - key: ''
    value: King Munjong (文宗) represents this work's ideal of virtuous rulership through frugality, merit-based administration, and restraint of factional power—a historical standard by which the present is found lacking.
  - key: ''
    value: Myojeong (妙淸) was a controversial Buddhist-Daoist figure at the Goryeo court who wielded dangerous political influence, similar to Lin Lingsu in the Chinese precedent cited.
